text: This is a bit of a random post, but might be useful for some. As long as you are "fighting", resenting, seriously arguing with your mother, you're still spiritually a child. My mum is naturally controlling - all Slavic mothers are - just accept her as it is, try not to sadden her

Younger bros who are still in HS, living at home, have not moved out, etc. - remember whatever your mother does, she does out of love. Of course follow your own instincts, be free, but make sure to not sadden her, make sure she knows she is loved and respected.

A very good piece of advice by @heropilled that I now regularly use: "When buying a pineapple, always get the one that reminds you the most of the sun." It seems vague, but once you are standing in the supermarket fruit aisle, you will understand it, it is all instinct, feel.

Understanding the Bulgarian national condition under Ottomanism as being not nearly as bad as portrayed does not take any of the April Uprising's glory away - on the contrary, by removing the emotional veil, it proudly exposes the revolution's true purpose - holy national liberty

Any peoples is able to revolt when put to torture and genocide - doing it in pleasant conditions, a clean cage - a far more heroic endeavor, motivated only by a love of almost metaphysical liberty and a sacred impulse of establishing borders of one's own.

I think every European country has an important choice to make about its national heroes, kings, etc.

Either preserve their holiness in the mist of ignorance, and keep them away from the living, or go the American way and "brandify" them - hoping to rekindle reverence and love.

It is mostly about love versus pure respect. American figures today feel more like characters in a novel, it does not feel wrong to include them in jokes, "memes", they "kick ass", there is beloved and cute T. Roosevelt. Can't imagine doing this for a Romanian voivoda or king...
